  "opinion": "As a cleaner in Naples with three kids and a background that’s mostly hands-on work, I see the gender gap in science not as some abstract statistic but as something that affects real people right here. When I talk to my neighbors or the kids at school, I hear stories of girls being told they’re not 'good at math' or boys being discouraged from creative thinking. The gap isn’t just about who’s in labs or engineering—it’s about how society treats kids from different backgrounds. My parents had different education levels, but they both taught me that curiosity matters more than grades. In Naples, where the streets are full of stories and the ocean is always calling, I’ve seen how little things like a girl not being encouraged to ask questions can keep her from seeing herself in science. Should we address it? Absolutely. But not with big speeches or top-down policies. Start small: let kids play with science in the park, help them see that math is part of everyday life, not just a test. My own creativity comes from fixing things around the house—like when I mend a bike chain or knit a sweater. If we can make science feel like that kind of hands-on, real-world work, then girls and boys will see themselves in it. It’s not about changing the system overnight. It’s about showing up, day by day, with the same patience I give my kids when they’re learning to ride a bike.",
